1. perbelle: upon per in com· pounds, cf. Intr. 77. Bellefacis, boue facis, etc, are colloquial phrases to express gratitude. Cf. bene bem'g- nequc arbitror te facere, Plaut. Most. 8163 bene hercle sactum et habco vobis gratiam, Rud. 835.— Tyrannionis: a grammarian aud teacher who was brought to Rome as a prisoner by L. Lucullus. He uasat one time tutor oi the young Cicero. His services in arranging Cicero's books are mentioned iu Att4.8n; Q. sr. 3. 4. 5, and Ep. XXIII. 6 also. The place in which this letter was written is deter- mined by comparing it with Att. 4. 8 Α.- tuis librariolis: cf. Intr. 58. Some of Cicero’s works were probably published by Atticus; cf. Ate. 2. 1. 2 tu, si tibi placuerit liber, curabis ut et Athenis sit ct in cete· ris oppidis Graeciae—duos ali- quos: an indefinite small number ; cf. Cic. de Fr'n. 2. 62 tres aliqui out quattuor. — glutinatoribus: strips of papyrus from 8 to 14 'uches long and 3 to 12 inches

wide were pasted together (gluti- nare) at the sides in the proper order after they had been written upon. A stick was fastened to the last sheet, and on this the book was rolled into a volumen. The ends of the stick were furnished with knobs (cornua), to the upper one was attached a strip of parch- ment containing the title (index). Cf.
